            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Zayn Rahman\u2019s story is written in the fog and coded in the timelines of Adobe Premiere. The son of Bangladeshi immigrants, his early years were spent in a cramped Tenderloin apartment, the symphony of city sirens his nightly lullaby. His father drove a taxi, navigating the city\u2019s steep hills with a quiet resilience, while his mother worked long hours at a laundromat. For them, San Francisco was a promise of opportunity, one they hoped their son would seize through traditional academics.\n\nBut Zayn struggled in the rigid structure of school. He wasn't a book learner; his mind worked visually, absorbing the world through frames and motion. He found his calling not in textbooks, but in a high school digital media vocational program. While his parents fretted, Zayn flourished. The language of timelines and color grading made more sense to him than algebra. It was a turning point, a validation that his different way of seeing the world had value. He used his skills to create a short documentary about his father\u2019s life as a cab driver, a piece filled with such empathy and visual flair that it finally won his parents\u2019 full support.\n\nAfter graduation, he landed an internship and then a junior video editor position at a small media company in SoMa that creates informational content for tech clients. Now 24, he lives in the Outer Richmond with two roommates, a short bus ride from his parents. His $65,000 salary is a constant balancing act against rent, but he feels a quiet pride in his independence.\n\nHis daily routine is quintessentially San Franciscan: a brisk walk through the damp morning fog to the Muni stop, the 3.5-mile ride downtown spent listening to podcasts on sound design, and an eight-hour day of splicing together marketing reels and internal training videos. Evenings are for affordable dinners\u2014often his mother\u2019s cooking dropped off in Tupperware\u2014and late nights spent on his passion project: a documentary series about the city\u2019s vanishing legacy businesses.\n\nZayn\u2019s San Francisco isn't the glittering world of tech IPOs, but the one of neighborhood bakeries, immigrant stories, and the shared rhythm of public transport. He dreams of one day editing feature films, of telling stories that matter. For now, he finds meaning in the steady craft, honing his skills one frame at a time, a true son of the city he so carefully documents."
        },
